CONTENT are the syntactically correct expressions that convey information such as reports, tasks, orders, requests and plans. Expressions are the payload of C-BML messages that also contains METADATA.
METADATA information elements may be required to disseminate the payload, specify information exchange policies, or provide references that may be used in the processing of the message.
WHERE constituents denote spatial aspects such as locations, routes or directions.
WHAT constituents are predominantly "verbs" and denote actions or events. Actions are used to specify tasks while events are used for reports.
WHEN constituents denote timing information that may be relative or absolute. Relative timings refer to actions while absolute timings use a date-time element.
WHY constituents specify a desired end state.
WHO constituents primarily denote organisations. They also may specify facilities or control features.
